function allPathsSourceTarget(graph) {
    const result = [];
    const path = [];
    DFS(graph, result, path, 0);
    return result;
}

function DFS(graph, result, path, currentNode) {
    path.push(currentNode);
    if (currentNode === graph.length - 1) {
        result.push(path.slice());
    } else {
        for (const neighbor of graph[currentNode]) {
            DFS(graph, result, path, neighbor);
        }
    }
    path.pop();
}
```

    This algorithm uses a Depth First Search (DFS) approach to traverse through the directed acyclic graph. 

1. Create a recursive helper function called DFS, which takes the current node, path, graph, and result as parameters.
2. Add the current node to the path list.
3. Check if the current node is the target node (n-1).
   - If yes, then add the path to the result list.
4. If the current node is not the target, traverse through each of its neighbors by calling the DFS function recursively.
5. Pop off the current node from the path to backtrack to the previous node.
6. The main function calls the DFS function with node 0 as the starting point, and it returns the result list containing all possible paths.

The time complexity of this algorithm is O(2^N * N) as in the worst case, we will iterate through all the paths from the starting node to the target node. The space complexity is also O(2^N * N) because of the storage required for the result list.

